[[Colonel]] [[the Honourable]] '''Charles Ingram''' (27 March 1696 – 28 November 1748), was a British soldier and politician.

Ingram was the seventh son of [[Arthur Ingram, 3rd Viscount of Irvine]], by Isabella Machel, daughter of [[John Machell (MP for Horsham)|John Machell]], [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Horsham (UK Parliament constituency)|Horsham]], of Hills, [[Sussex]]. He was a [[general]] in the [[British Army]].<ref name="cracroft">[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1540.htm?zoom_highlight=Viscount+Irvine www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk Irvine, Viscount of (S, 1661 - 1778)]</ref> In 1737 he was returned to Parliament for Horsham (succeeding his elder brother [[Henry Ingram, 7th Viscount of Irvine|Henry]]), a seat he held until his death.<ref name="cracroft"/><ref>{{Rayment-hc|h|4|date=June 2012}}</ref>

Ingram married Elizabeth Scarborough, daughter and co-heiress of Charles Scarborough, Clerk of the [[Board of Green Cloth]], of [[Windsor, Berkshire]], in 1726. They had one son, [[Charles Ingram, 9th Viscount of Irvine|Charles]], later 9th [[Viscount of Irvine]], and three daughters. Elizabeth died in December 1739. Ingram survived her by nine years and died in November 1748, aged 52.<ref name="cracroft"/>

